abstract = {Hearing parents of deaf and hard-of-hearing (DHH) children often struggle to provide meaningful sign inputs while learning a new language themselves. This work aims to understand the needs and challenges of hearing parents to use American Sign Language (ASL) when interacting with their DHH children, as well as preferences regarding AI-mediated communication technologies that support face-to-face interaction in ASL with DHH children. We adopted the technology probe design method to investigate key design elements that contribute to the usefulness of ASL recommendations and user autonomy in AI-mediated technologies. Findings of a semi-structured interview study show that ASL recommendations are considered useful when they align with users’ needs, and offer diversity and serendipity. In addition, participants desire more control over automatic recommendations, but more autonomy does not always guarantee greater user satisfaction. We conclude with design insights for future AI-mediated communication technologies for parent-child interactions.},
